entry.title: IndexedDB: rename IndexedDBBucketState to IndexedDBBucketContext
entry.content:
Also clean up some obsolete docs, and add new docs explaining the

intended role of this class in a system where IDB runs on multiple

sequences.



The intent is to partition sequence usage along class boundaries, where

`IndexedDBFactory` stays on the main IDB sequence, and

`IndexedDBBucketContext` is created and run on a separate sequence via

`SequenceBound`. The backing store and related implementation classes

live on the BucketContext sequence, while `IndexedDBFactory`,

`IndexedDBDispatcherHost`, and `IndexedDBContextImpl` live on the main

sequence. (However, some of these classes will be merged and/or

factored away and/or renamed --- in particular, IndexedDBDispatcherHost

is a relic that can be dissolved and reabsorbed into other nearby

classes.)



Main-sequence code that needs to interact with bucket code will do so

via SequenceBound, which makes async calls across sequence

boundaries very easy.



Bucket-sequence code that needs to call out to other services will use

a combination of:

* callbacks provided by main-sequence code (some of this already exists

in the form of `notify_tasks_callback_` and `tear_down_callback_`)

* direct communication with other services, such as

`QuotaManagerProxy`, which is already thread-safe, or

`BlobStorageContext`, which is already a mojoified service



It will also likely be a good idea to move bucket-sequence code into its

own subdirectory in order to make this split more apparent.



Bug: 1474996

entry.title: Refactor QuicSession's netlog calls
entry.content:
* Better document the parameters exposed by QUIC_CONNECTION_MIGRATION*

type of events

* Add two new QUIC_CONNECTION_MIGRATION types:

* QUIC_CONNECTION_MIGRATION_WAITING_FOR_NEW_NETWORK to track

scenarios where connection migration doesn't close a session but

instead waits for a new network

* QUIC_CONNECTION_MIGRATION_FAILURE_WAITING_FOR_NETWORK to report

a failed wait

* QUIC_CONNECTION_MIGRATION_SUCCESS_WAITING_FOR_NETWORK to report

a successful wait (migration itself could still fail)

* Add QUIC_SESSION_NETWORK* type of events, decoupled from connection

migration. These are useful to still study the propagation of

network change signals when connection migration is disabled

entry.title: [reland 2] content: unconditionally populate frame_url in ContextMenuParams
entry.content:
The prior design only populated frame_url when the initiating frame was

a subframe, which led to code in quite a few places to use frame_url if

present and page_url otherwise, or to test for an empty frame_url as a

signal that the initiator was a subframe.



This change makes frame_url unconditional, and adds a separate parameter

for whether the initiator is a subframe. It also refactors

TestRenderViewContextMenu slightly to make some of the factory arguments

for that class optional, since nearly all call sites pass the same

values.



This is a preparatory refactor for a behavior change in passing invoker

origins through the context menu.



This change is a re-land of

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4790929,

which introduced an MSan test failure because of the uninitialized

is_subframe member in ContextMenuParams.



This change is a subsequent re-land of

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4827951, which

introduced a branded lens build test failure on ChromeOS that the CQ

bots didn't catch.

entry.title: [iOS][byot] Support lazy loading tabs and use it in BringAndroidTabs
entry.content:
This CL supports lazy loading options in TabInsertionBrowserAgent and

UrlLoadingBrowserAgent, and changes the behavior when users "open"

tabs from BYOT. Instead of loading all the tabs at once, it only loads

the first 6 (enough to fill the tab grid) and adds the rest to the tab

grid without loading them. In the tab grid, the user would see the

title of the page in the grid, and the page only loads if the user taps

on the grid to open it.



This is done by turning each remote tab into a CRWSessionStorage,

use the storage object to create an unrealized web state, and add it

to the web state list. Also the option to lazy load tabs and place-

holder title is added to UrlLoadingParams.

entry.title: [import-attributes] Throw on invalid attributes keys
entry.content:
In the past six months, the old import assertions proposal has been

renamed to "import attributes" with the follwing major changes:

1. the keyword is now `with` instead of `assert`

2. unknown assertions cause an error rather than being ignored



(1) has been implemented in V8 at [v8-patch], under the

`--harmony-import-attributes` flag. This patch implements (2), that due

to how module loading is layered must be implemented in Chromium.



Implementing this change uncovered a bogous assertion in the HTML spec:

this patch implements the fix proposed at [html-assertion-fix], that

adds a check for invalid attributes in the "create a JavaScript module

script" algorithm.



WPT have been merged at [wpt], and tests for the additional HTML PR are

being reviewed at [wpt2]. This patch passes all the tests in the

import-assertions and import-attributes folders.

entry.title: [WAAPI] Do not cancel an animation that has its effect reset.
entry.content:
When an effect is associated with an animation, it resets the effect

on the animation it was previously associated with. We were handling

the handoff correctly in Animation::setEffect, but not in the

constructor. The previous animation should not get canceled. After

resetting the effect, the effect end time becomes zero and the old

animation should be in the finished rather than idle play state. This

change has no visual effect as even if the old animation had a fill

mode set to 'forward' or "both', this fill mode will also get reset

when the effect is reset. A finished animation without a fill mode

is inactive. The distinction is only really observable

via web-animation API calls. Likely why it took this many years to

notice the issue.



Manually verified the new test on Firefox nightly as well. Reportedly,

webkit has the correct behavior as well, though not verified.
